# 0014. Longest Common Prefix

**Problem Name:** Longest Common Prefix  
**Difficulty:** Easy

---

## Question

Write a function to find the **longest common prefix** string amongst an array of strings.

If there is no common prefix, return an empty string `""`.

---

## My Solution

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    string longestCommonPrefix(vector<string>& strs) {
        if (strs.empty())
            return "";

        string prefix = strs[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < strs.size(); i++) {
            while (strs[i].find(prefix) != 0) {
                prefix.pop_back();

                if (prefix.empty())
                    return "";
            }
        }

        return prefix;
    }
};
```

---

## Complexity

| Metric | Value |
|--------|-------|
| **Time Complexity** | `O(n × m)` |
| **Space Complexity** | `O(1)` |

> Where:
> - `n` = Number of strings
> - `m` = Length of the longest common prefix

---

## What I Learned

This problem helped me understand that I don't always need to compare every character of every string manually.

Instead, I can assume the first string is the common prefix and keep reducing it until every other string starts with it. Using functions like `find()` and `pop_back()` makes the solution much simpler and easier to write.

It also reinforced the idea of gradually narrowing down a possible answer instead of building one from scratch.

---

## Personal Notes

At first, I thought about comparing characters one by one across all strings, but that approach felt more complicated. After learning this method, I realized that treating the first string as the initial answer and shrinking it whenever needed makes the code much cleaner.

This problem also introduced me to a useful string-processing pattern that can be applied in many interview questions. Sometimes the simplest idea turns out to be the most efficient one.

